default&#xa0;
defaultLyme Bay
default - summary
default&#xa0;
defaultBLUE has discovered in its project in Lyme Bay, a European marine site, that regulation on its own does not make for a successful marine protected area.  It is a necessary and essential part of the picture but there are occasions where the vision and facilitation that can be achieved through co-management on the ground can achieve an even better result, one where the financial and community benefits are tangible to the existing users of the sea and the MPA plays a valued part in community life.  
default&#xa0;
defaultIt has often been overlooked that both European sites and MCZs will continue to be fished, so the fish and shellfish that comes from them, provided it is caught according to the agreed management measures for the site, offers greater reassurance to retailers and to consumer
defaults
default themselves that it is from a sustainably managed source.  It may even be possible in the future to develop a certification scheme that applies to seafood caught from such sites, with the effect of creating demand and value for fishermen’s produce, and building in their support for the area, even where the volumes extracted are lower than they were before.  We would invite the committee to examine the benefits and the constraints of this approach and to ask themselves whether the necessary flexibility of regulation currently exists on the ground.
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
defaultLyme Bay background
default&#xa0;defaultLyme Bay’s rocky reefs are known as
default 
default”England’s coral garden.”  The 
defaultreef 
defaultarea is protected as a European marine site for its globally significant flora and fauna
default- and there is a new MCZ as well as a European SAC
default.  It is also home to an active fishing community and supports a significant tourism trade. A closure to destructive trawling and dredging was implemented 
defaultinitially 
defaultacross 
default60 
defaultq miles of the reefs in 2008, through a statutory instrument.  This ban on mobile gears had the unexpected effect of increasing fishing pressure from 
defaultpots and set nets to such a degree that it led to unsustainable fishing, economic damage to fishermen’s livelihoods and potentially a threat to the recovery of the protected reef. 
default&#xa0;
defaultCreating a working groupdefaultIn an attempt to solve the problems caused by the closure, BLUE convened informal meetings with fishermen, regulators and conservationists. This was an achievement in itself as these meetings brought together traditionally ‘warring’ parties around the same table and, as a result, together they formed a new body, spanning two IFCA areas, the Lyme Bay Working Group. 
default&#xa0;
defaultSince then (2011) BLUE has been working with the local fishermen to devise a model of self-management which financially benefits and motivates fishing communities to fish in more sustainable ways. 
defaultThis project has been hailed as a “world-first” by Fishing News given its radical collaborative approach involving fishermen in stock management and research.
default&#xa0;
default“
default….those involved in Lyme Bay fishing have come together with all the bodies involved in seeking to preserve the ecological balance, and defaultthey have together drawn up a remarkable voluntary codedefault……Lyme Bay is leading the way.”defaultOliver Letwin, Conservative MP for West Dorset.
