default&#xa0;default“It’s a win-win situation for all involved. It’s good for the fish, good for us fisherman, the environment and it shows what a good scheme it is because it’s now going national.”
defaultAlex Jones, Lyme Bay fisherman.
default&#xa0;defaultSummarydefault&#xa0;defaultThis project located in England’s very own “coral garden” offers a “win-win-win” for fishermen, conservationists and communities. 
defaultIn short, the fishermen will play an important role in creating a sustainable future for their businesses and benefit from an enhanced market for premium quality, sustainably caught fish; conservationists will benefit from scientific data collected by the fishermen which will act as a foundation for the conservation and protection of sensitive habitats and species both in Lyme Bay and throughout the UK;  and communities will benefit from an enhanced local economy (from both fisheries and tourism). 
defaultKey outcomes will be an improved market for premium
default 
default“sustainably-caught” Lyme Bay seafood that can be branded and labelled as such, the collection of important scientific data to inform marine planning and importantly
default defaultthe 
defaultestablishment of a model project for roll out to other coastal areas in the UK.
default&#xa0;
default defaultAdopting the Lyme Bay model elsewhere in the UKdefault&#xa0;
defaultThe aim of the Lyme Bay project was always that it would become a blueprint for successful, 
defaultpragmatic marine conservation. The basic framework of the Lyme Bay model can be applied to any Marine Protected Area (MPA), Special Area of Conservation (SAC) or Marine Conservation Zone (MCZ) around the coast and much of the work done in Lyme Bay can be used in full or in part depending on the nature of the fishery and the marine site. In September 2013 BLUE hosted a conference at the National Sailing Academy in Weymouth attracting 170 delegates. The day was used as an opportunity to share BLUE’s experiences from Lyme as well as offering a platform to fishers, regulators and conservationists from around the UK to discuss challenges and opportunities from their regions. Following on from the conference more than 10 sites around the UK approached BLUE looking for support. 
default&#xa0;
defaultIt is not possible yet to name the areas, as this should remain confidential between them and BLUE until they are comfortable about going public, but this might be possible by the time of the committee’s evidence session.  BLUE is currently carrying out a feasibility study in each of these areas to gain a better understanding of the area, key stakeholders and to identify how and where best to can get involved. In early 2014 BLUE will be shortlisting these candidate sites ready to develop two or three projects in these areas.
default&#xa0;
defaultThe key benefits of translating the Lyme model to other areas of the country are: 
default&#xa0;
default1)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe facilitation of a shared vision between different stakeholders, managers, fishermen of several gear types and tourism and community interests.
default2)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe potential to generate additional funding from charity funders to carry out projects that coincide with the management objectives for the area when public funding faces constraints.
default3)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe involvement of retailers in developing brands based on sustainable fishing systems
default within or adjacent to MPAs
default. 
